(* Beginning of Notebook Content *)
Notebook[{
Cell["\<\
Geometry Theorems: Lean 4 Proofs, Verified in Wolfram Language\
\>", "Title"],

Cell["A computer-algebra companion to MyProject/Geometry.lean", "Subtitle"],

Cell["\<\
This notebook mirrors, theorem by theorem, the six plane-geometry theorems \
that are formally proved in Lean 4 in MyProject/Geometry.lean of this \
project. Each section states the theorem, names the corresponding Lean \
theorem, and verifies it symbolically. Evaluate the whole notebook with \
Evaluation > Evaluate Notebook; every check should return True.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Important difference: Wolfram's Simplify is a computer-algebra check -- you \
trust the CAS implementation. Lean is a proof assistant: every step is \
verified by a small logical kernel, so a successful compile IS the proof. The \
math content, however, is exactly the same: points are integer (here: \
symbolic) coordinates, and each geometric statement is translated into an \
algebraic identity.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["Setup: points, vectors, dot product, squared distance", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
Same definitions as the Lean file. Note that A, B, C, D, N are reserved \
symbols in Wolfram Language, so points are named pA, pB, pC, pD and midpoints \
mM, mN.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
vec[a_, b_] := b - a        (* vector from a to b *)
dot[u_, v_] := u . v         (* dot product *)
distSq[a_, b_] := (b - a) . (b - a)   (* squared distance *)\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
pA = {ax, ay}; pB = {bx, by}; pC = {cx, cy};  (* symbolic points *)\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["Theorem 1: symmetry of distance  (Lean: distSq_symm)", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
|AB|^2 = |BA|^2. In Lean this needs the expansion (a-b)^2 = (b-a)^2 plus \
commutativity rewrites; here Simplify does the algebra.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["Simplify[distSq[pA, pB] == distSq[pB, pA]]", "Input"],

Cell["Theorem 2: Pythagorean theorem  (Lean: pythagoras)", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
If the angle at A is right (dot product of vectors AB and AC is zero) then \
|BC|^2 = |AB|^2 + |AC|^2. The key identity, proved as pythagoras_vec in Lean, \
is that |BC|^2 - |AB|^2 - |AC|^2 = -2 (AB . AC) identically. So the \
difference plus 2 (AB . AC) expands to exactly 0:\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Expand[distSq[pB, pC] - distSq[pA, pB] - distSq[pA, pC] + 2 dot[vec[pA, pB], \
vec[pA, pC]]] === 0\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
Equivalently, assume the right angle and let Simplify use it:\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Simplify[distSq[pB, pC] == distSq[pA, pB] + distSq[pA, pC], Assumptions -> \
dot[vec[pA, pB], vec[pA, pC]] == 0]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
Theorem 3: the 3-4-5 right triangle  (Lean: pythagoras_3_4_5)\
\>", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
A concrete instance: O(0,0), A(3,0), B(0,4). In Lean the tactic `decide` just \
computes both sides; here the kernel evaluates them too.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
distSq[{3, 0}, {0, 4}] == distSq[{0, 0}, {3, 0}] + distSq[{0, 0}, {0, 4}]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
{distSq[{3, 0}, {0, 4}], distSq[{0, 0}, {3, 0}], distSq[{0, 0}, {0, 4}]}   (* \
25 = 9 + 16 *)\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["Theorem 4: triangle midsegment  (Lean: midsegment)", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
mM and mN are the midpoints of AB and AC. The single vector equation 2 MN = \
BC encodes both conclusions of the midsegment theorem: MN is parallel to BC \
and half its length. (Lean states the midpoint condition as 2M = A + B to \
stay inside the integers; over the rationals we can just divide by 2.)\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
mM = (pA + pB)/2; mN = (pA + pC)/2;
Simplify[2 vec[mM, mN] == vec[pB, pC]]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
Theorem 5: parallelogram diagonals bisect each other  (Lean: \
parallelogram_diag)\
\>", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
ABCD is a parallelogram when vector AB equals vector DC, i.e. pD = pC - \
vec(A,B). Then the midpoints of the two diagonals AC and BD coincide.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
pD = pC - vec[pA, pB];
Simplify[(pA + pC)/2 == (pB + pD)/2]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["\<\
Theorem 6: centroid divides the median 2 : 1  (Lean: centroid_divides)\
\>", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
G = (A + B + C)/3 is the centroid and mBC the midpoint of BC. The vector \
equation AG = 2 GM says G lies on the median from A and divides it in ratio 2 \
: 1.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
pG = (pA + pB + pC)/3; mBC = (pB + pC)/2;
Simplify[vec[pA, pG] == 2 vec[pG, mBC]]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["Picture: the 3-4-5 triangle and its midsegment", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
The red segment joins the midpoints of the two legs; by Theorem 4 it is \
parallel to the hypotenuse and half as long.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Graphics[{
  EdgeForm[{Thick, Black}], FaceForm[LightBlue],
  Polygon[{{0, 0}, {3, 0}, {0, 4}}],
  Red, Thick, Line[{{3/2, 0}, {0, 2}}],
  Black, PointSize[Large],
  Point[{{0, 0}, {3, 0}, {0, 4}, {3/2, 0}, {0, 2}}],
  Text[Style[\"O (0,0)\", 12], {0, 0}, {1.3, 1.3}],
  Text[Style[\"A (3,0)\", 12], {3, 0}, {-1.2, 1.3}],
  Text[Style[\"B (0,4)\", 12], {0, 4}, {1.2, -1.3}],
  Text[Style[\"midsegment\", 12, Red], {3/4, 1}, {-1.2, -1}]
}, Axes -> True, PlotRange -> {{-1, 4}, {-1, 5}}]\
\>", "Input"],

Cell["Where to go next", "Section"],

Cell["\<\
The Lean file proves the same statements with machine-checked rigor using \
only core tactics (simp, rw, omega, decide). To see it, open \
MyProject/Geometry.lean and run `lake build` -- a successful build means the \
Lean kernel accepted every proof. Try changing a conclusion (e.g. the 2:1 \
ratio to 3:1) and watch Lean reject it, then try the same experiment here \
with Simplify returning False instead of True.\
\>", "Text"]
},
WindowSize->{960, 900},
FrontEndVersion->"12.3 for Mac OS X x86 (64-bit) (May 11, 2021)",
StyleDefinitions->"Default.nb"
]
(* End of Notebook Content *)

